      <h1 class="font-heading text-3xl sm:text-4xl md:text-5xl leading-tight">How Long Does Hardwood Floor Installation Take in Houston?</h1>
      <p class="mt-4 text-brand-ink/70 text-sm">Published May 2026 · By Joey Jamail</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <article class="container mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 pb-16 max-w-3xl text-brand-ink/90 leading-relaxed text-[1.0625rem]">

    <p>For a typical Houston home — 1,500 to 3,000 square feet of hardwood — a professionally installed engineered hardwood floor takes <strong>5 to 10 working days from demo to walk-on-ready</strong>. Bigger homes, complex patterns, or messy subfloors push that longer. Smaller, simpler projects can finish in 3 to 5 days.</p>

    <p class="mt-4">But that's the short answer. The more useful question is: <strong>what happens on each day, and what can slow it down?</strong> Because if you're living in the house during the install (most of our clients do), the day-by-day matters more than the total.</p>

    <p class="mt-4">If you want to skip ahead and just get a real timeline for your house, <a href={BOOKING_URL} target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer" class="text-brand-brass hover:underline font-semibold">book a free consultation</a> — we'll measure, look at your subfloor, and tell you exactly how many days.</p>

    <h2 class="font-heading text-2xl sm:text-3xl text-brand-coal mt-10 mb-4">Quick answer: typical Houston install timelines</h2>
    <p>For engineered European white oak, installed with a typical glue-down method on a Houston slab-on-grade home:</p>
    <ul class="mt-3 space-y-2 list-disc pl-6">
      <li><strong>800–1,200 sq ft</strong> (small condo or single floor): 3–5 working days</li>
      <li><strong>1,500–2,500 sq ft</strong> (typical Houston bungalow or townhome): 5–7 working days</li>
      <li><strong>2,500–3,500 sq ft</strong> (Memorial-sized downstairs): 7–9 working days</li>
      <li><strong>3,500–5,000+ sq ft</strong> (large home, whole-floor install): 9–12 working days</li>
      <li><strong>Complex patterns</strong> (herringbone, chevron, custom): Add 30–50% to the above</li>
    </ul>
    <p class="mt-4">These are <strong>working days</strong>, not calendar days. A 7-working-day install starting on a Monday finishes the following Tuesday or Wednesday. We don't work on weekends as a rule — but we will if a project needs it to make a move-in date.</p>

    <h2 class="font-heading text-2xl sm:text-3xl text-brand-coal mt-10 mb-4">Day-by-day: what an install actually looks like</h2>
    <p>Here's what a typical 2,000 sq ft Houston home install looks like day-by-day. Your project may compress or expand depending on subfloor condition, but this is the shape of it.</p>

    <h3 class="font-heading text-xl text-brand-coal mt-8 mb-3">Day 0 (Pre-Install): Material acclimation</h3>
    <p>Before we touch your floor, your hardwood needs to acclimate to your home's humidity. We deliver the material 48–72 hours before install day and stack it in the rooms where it's going. The boxes stay closed, but the planks need time to equalize with your home's air.</p>
    <p class="mt-3">This is non-negotiable in Houston. Skipping acclimation is the single most common cause of installed floors cupping, gapping, or buckling six months later. If an installer doesn't deliver and acclimate before install day, find a different installer.</p>

    <h3 class="font-heading text-xl text-brand-coal mt-8 mb-3">Day 1: Demo</h3>
    <p>The first thing we do is get the existing floor out.</p>
    <ul class="mt-3 space-y-2 list-disc pl-6">
      <li><strong>Carpet:</strong> A morning. Roll it up, haul it out.</li>
      <li><strong>Laminate or floating LVP:</strong> A morning to early afternoon. Pull boards, dispose.</li>
      <li><strong>Glued-down vinyl or hardwood:</strong> A full day. Scraping adhesive is slow work.</li>
      <li><strong>Ceramic tile:</strong> 1 to 2 full days for a downstairs Houston install. Tile demo is loud, dusty, and the slow part of the project. Old thinset has to come off the slab.</li>
    </ul>
    <p class="mt-3">We protect everything that isn't being removed: walls, doors, baseboards (if staying), cabinetry, fixtures. Dust containment goes up — typically zip-wall plastic barriers and HEPA-filtered air scrubbers running through the install.</p>

    <h3 class="font-heading text-xl text-brand-coal mt-8 mb-3">Day 2: Subfloor prep</h3>
    <p>This is the day a lot of homeowners don't expect. The subfloor is rarely ready to glue hardwood to right after demo.</p>
    <ul class="mt-3 space-y-2 list-disc pl-6">
      <li><strong>Moisture testing:</strong> We test the slab with both calcium chloride and RH probes. Houston slabs often read high.</li>
      <li><strong>Moisture mitigation:</strong> If needed, we apply a moisture-mitigation coating — usually a roller-applied epoxy. It needs to cure overnight.</li>
      <li><strong>Leveling:</strong> Slabs are rarely flat enough for wide-plank hardwood. Self-leveling compound goes down, fills the low spots, and cures.</li>
      <li><strong>Grinding:</strong> Old adhesive residue, paint splatters, and bumps get ground down.</li>
      <li><strong>Final cleanup:</strong> The slab is vacuumed clean. Any speck of debris under glue-down hardwood becomes a visible bump.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3 class="font-heading text-xl text-brand-coal mt-8 mb-3">Days 3–6: Installation</h3>
    <p>This is the actual hardwood install. For a 2,000 sq ft home, it's typically 3 to 4 working days of installation, depending on:</p>
    <ul class="mt-3 space-y-2 list-disc pl-6">
      <li><strong>Plank width:</strong> Wider planks take longer (they require more careful placement)</li>
      <li><strong>Layout complexity:</strong> Straight-lay is fastest; diagonal adds 15–20%; herringbone or chevron can double the install time</li>
      <li><strong>Room shape:</strong> Boxes are fast; bay windows, alcoves, and built-ins slow things down</li>
    </ul>
    <p class="mt-3">Each day, the crew lays glue across a section of slab, sets planks, and works their way through the house room by room. The previous day's work is fully cured by morning and can be walked on by the crew (with care — full cure takes 24 hours).</p>

    <h3 class="font-heading text-xl text-brand-coal mt-8 mb-3">Day 7: Trim, transitions, and finish work</h3>
    <p>The last day is the day that separates a good install from a great one. Quarter-round or shoe molding, T-moldings, reducers at flooring transitions, stair-nose pieces, threshold pieces at exterior doors, undercut door jambs and trim so planks slide cleanly under.</p>
    <p class="mt-3">A cheap installer rushes this in two hours and you can tell forever. We give it a full day. By end of day, every transition is flush, every gap is closed, every nail is set.</p>

    <h3 class="font-heading text-xl text-brand-coal mt-8 mb-3">Day 8: Walk-on, final walk-through</h3>
    <p>24 hours after the last plank is glued, the floor is walk-on-ready. We do a final walk-through with you, point out any small touch-ups, and clean the floor for the first time using the products we recommend for ongoing care.</p>
    <p class="mt-3">Furniture can go back the next morning — give the glue a full 48 hours under heavy loads.</p>

    <h2 class="font-heading text-2xl sm:text-3xl text-brand-coal mt-10 mb-4">What slows a hardwood install down in Houston</h2>
    <p>Houston has its own set of timeline-killers. The most common:</p>
    <ul class="mt-3 space-y-2 list-disc pl-6">
      <li><strong>Slab moisture issues:</strong> If your slab reads very high for moisture, the moisture-mitigation coating adds a day, and very wet slabs may need a second coat.</li>
      <li><strong>Tile demo:</strong> Adds 1–2 full days vs. carpet demo. Plan for it if you have tile downstairs.</li>
      <li><strong>Existing damage:</strong> Soft spots in plywood subfloors, water damage from a long-ago leak, or old asbestos tile under newer flooring can all add days.</li>
      <li><strong>Coordinating with other trades:</strong> If you're doing a kitchen reno simultaneously, timing matters. We can flex — but it has to be planned.</li>
      <li><strong>Custom patterns:</strong> Herringbone or chevron in a large room can add 3–5 days vs. straight-lay.</li>
      <li><strong>Material delays:</strong> Special orders can mean 4–8 weeks before install day for the material to arrive.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2 class="font-heading text-2xl sm:text-3xl text-brand-coal mt-10 mb-4">Can I live in the house during installation?</h2>
    <p>Yes — most of our clients do. We've designed our process around occupied homes:</p>
    <ul class="mt-3 space-y-2 list-disc pl-6">
      <li><strong>HEPA-filtered air scrubbers</strong> run continuously, especially during demo</li>
      <li><strong>Zip-wall plastic barriers</strong> seal off the active install area from the rest of the house</li>
      <li><strong>Daily cleanup</strong> at the end of each work day so you have clean walkways</li>
      <li><strong>Pet protection plan</strong> if you have dogs or cats — we work around them, you keep them contained or out</li>
      <li><strong>Kitchen access:</strong> We sequence rooms so your kitchen is one of the last areas done, or the first done, depending on which is more disruptive for you</li>
    </ul>
    <p class="mt-3">Most families say the install was easier than they expected. The hard part is the anticipation; the actual week of work is usually fine.</p>

    <h2 class="font-heading text-2xl sm:text-3xl text-brand-coal mt-10 mb-4">How to plan your install timeline</h2>
    <p>When you're planning a hardwood install in Houston, count back from your "done" date:</p>
    <ul class="mt-3 space-y-2 list-disc pl-6">
      <li><strong>8 weeks out:</strong> Order samples, talk to installers</li>
      <li><strong>6 weeks out:</strong> Pick your floor, sign a contract, confirm material lead time</li>
      <li><strong>3 weeks out:</strong> We confirm install dates, you start prepping the house</li>
      <li><strong>3 days out:</strong> Material delivered for acclimation</li>
      <li><strong>Install week:</strong> 5–10 working days</li>
      <li><strong>Move-in / furniture-back:</strong> Day after final walk-through</li>
    </ul>
    <p class="mt-3">For new construction, work backward from your move-in date — and give yourself a week of buffer. Builders' schedules slip; install schedules shouldn't.</p>

